Design Requirement: No phase transformations (BCC↔FCC, ordering reactions, precipitation/dissolution) across full temperature envelope for each alloy's intended service environment.

1.1.2 Gibbs Free Energy Constraints

Strengthening phases must exhibit negative Gibbs free energy of formation at all service temperatures:

\Delta G_f = \Delta H_f - T\Delta S_f < 0 \quad \text{for all } T \in [T_{min}, T_{max}]

For T-phase in PSM-1: $\Delta G_f = -15.2 \text{ kJ/mol at 300K}$, with stability maintained to 400°C.

1.2 Radiation Kinetics and Damage Accumulation

Materials must maintain structural integrity under Galactic Cosmic Ray (GCR) and Solar Particle Event (SPE) spectra for mission durations of 3-10 years.

1.2.1 Diffusion Constraints

Sluggish diffusion kinetics are essential to suppress radiation-enhanced segregation and phase instability:

D_{self} < 10^{-20} \text{ m}^2/\text{s at } 300^\circ\text{C}

This criterion eliminates conventional Al alloys (D ~10⁻¹⁶ m²/s at 300°C) and justifies the UFG/HEA approach.

1.2.2 Defect Sink Density

High sink density promotes point defect recombination before cluster formation:

\rho_{sink} > 10^{15} \text{ m}^{-2}

For PSM-1, UFG boundaries provide $\rho_{gb} \approx 3 \times 10^6 \text{ m}^{-1}$, translating to sink strength $k^2 \approx 10^{15} \text{ m}^{-2}$.

1.2.3 Helium Management (v4.0 Addition)

Transmutation products (H, He) from neutron/GCR interactions cause grain boundary embrittlement. Materials must manage helium through:

1. Trapping at interfaces with controlled bubble nucleation sites
2. Low helium diffusivity to prevent grain boundary accumulation
3. Critical helium concentration >100 appm before embrittlement

Proposal 1.1: Add helium accumulation modeling to Phase 1 materials development, with validation through neutron irradiation at HFIR (ORNL) or BR2 (Belgium).

