4.6 Functionally Graded Materials Integration (v4.0 Addition)

4.6.1 FGM Design Principles

Functionally graded materials transition smoothly from metal to ceramic, eliminating discrete interfaces that fail under thermal cycling.

Gradient profile:

C(x) = C_{metal} + (C_{ceramic} - C_{metal}) \cdot \left(\frac{x}{t}\right)^n

Where:

· $C(x)$ = ceramic volume fraction at position x
· $t$ = total gradient thickness (2 mm)
· $n$ = gradient exponent (n=1 linear, n>1 ceramic-rich near surface)

For HTSM-1 thermal protection: n=0.5 (metal-rich gradient) to maximize toughness at interface.

4.6.2 In-Situ FGM Manufacturing via EB-PBF

Process steps:

1. Core build: 100% HTSM-1 powder from hopper A
2. Gradient start: Introduce ceramic powder from hopper B at low feed rate
3. Gradient progression: Increase hopper B feed rate linearly over 40 layers (2 mm)
4. Ceramic outer layer: 100% ceramic for final 20 layers (1 mm)

Interlayer mixing: Achieved via melt pool convection; ensures compositional gradient without sharp steps.

